cardie, France","Oudenaarde, Oost-Vlaanderen":"Oudenaarde, East Flanders, Belgium","Europa":"Europe","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Nesle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch and North German: from the personal name <i>Nelle</i>, a pet form of   Cornelius  .","South German: variant of   Nell   2.","Altered form of German   Knell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cornelius","meanings":["Dutch, German, Danish, and southern English: from the Latin personal name <i>Cornelius</i> (originally an old Roman surname, probably derived from <i>cornu</i> ‘horn’), borne by a 3rd-century pope and Christian saint. In England, this name is rarely found before the 16th century, when the name was brought to England from the Low Countries by Protestants, among whom it was also a popular name in the vernacular form <i>Cornelis</i>. In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the German or Dutch variant <b>Kornelius</b>."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Soissons","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: from a variant of Old French <i>soçon</i>, <i>sosson</i> ‘companion, partner, workmate’ (from Latin <i>socius</i>), hence a nickname for a laborer, perhaps one who usually worked alongside a horse or ox."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Adèle de Nesle de Soissons was born about 1222, in Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France as the daughter of Jean DE NESLE II. She married Graf Jan I van Oudenaarde about 1250, in Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1255, at the age of 34."},"et":{"ABT 1222–1255":"umbes 1222–1255","1222–1255":"1222–1255","1222–1293":"1222–1293","1240–1280":"1240–1280","1240–1296":"1240–1296","1246–1290":"1246–1290","1250–1296":"1250–1296","1255–1305":"1255–1305","–Male":"Surnud","1296":"1296","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1293":"1293","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1305":"1305","ABT 1250":"umbes 1250","ABT 1240":"1240","1246":"1246","ABT 1222":"umbes 1222","1255":"1255","1222":"1222","of,Soissons,Aisne,France":"Soissons, Aisne, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Oudenaarde, Oost-Vlaanderen":"Oudenaarde, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Europa":"Europe","France":"Prantsusm